### Two Distinct Output Channels for UserPromptSubmit Hooks

Cross-referencing all four registered UserPromptSubmit hooks against their output formats reveals two structurally different injection mechanisms:

| Hook | Output field | Effect |
|------|-------------|--------|
| `recall-retrieve.js` | `additionalContext` | Injected as pre-prompt context block, attributed to system |
| `masonry-register.js` | `additionalContext` | Injected as pre-prompt context block, attributed to system |
| `masonry-prompt-router.js` | `hookSpecificOutput.content` | Mechanism unclear — see analysis below |
| `masonry-prompt-inject.js` | `additionalContext` | Injected as pre-prompt context block, attributed to system |

The `additionalContext` output format is the Claude Code UserPromptSubmit spec for context injection (confirmed in bl-audit M1.3 and M1.4; see `masonry/src/hooks/masonry-register.js` line 91: `process.stdout.write(JSON.stringify({ additionalContext: text }))`).

The `hookSpecificOutput` format is the same field name used by hooks on other event types:
- `masonry-approver.js` (PreToolUse) uses `hookSpecificOutput` with `permissionDecision: "allow"` — a decision field that produces enforced behavior (tool invocation is explicitly allowed or blocked)
- `masonry-pre-protect.js` (PreToolUse) uses `decision: "block"` — also produces enforced behavior
- `masonry-session-start.js` (SessionStart) uses `hookSpecificOutput.content` to inject context at session open

For UserPromptSubmit, the Claude Code spec defines `additionalContext` as the field for injecting content into the conversation. The `hookSpecificOutput.content` field is used by other hook types for decision signals, not for context injection. When `hookSpecificOutput` is emitted from a UserPromptSubmit hook, the behavior is ambiguous: it may be displayed or logged but does not follow the same `additionalContext` injection pathway.

